ok illustrates how ideas about fungibility, fugitivity, carcerality, marronage, sovereignty, placemaking, and governance shape the ways Black and Indigenous intellectuals narrate the past, present, and future. In turning to speculative fiction, Rifkin illustrates how speculation as a process provides conceptual and ethical resources for recognizing difference while engaging across it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Indians. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teaching. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aIndians of North AmericaxColonization. 0aIndians of North AmericaxStudy and teaching. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacexPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSpeculative fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005285zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005285.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles